      "rationale": "Nonlinear solver residuals converged to below 1e-5 for all 120 load increments across all 11 simulation instances. Energy balance error remained below 0.05% throughout loading. No unconverged load steps were recorded. Automatic time-stepping with bisection was employed; no manual overrides were required."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of simulation setup by a second analyst; checklist-based review documented.",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup was reviewed by an independent senior analyst using a pre-defined 47-item checklist covering geometry import, material assignment, contact definitions, boundary conditions, and output requests. Two minor discrepancies identified (incorrect friction coefficient in one sub-assembly contact pair; misaligned coordinate system in post-processing script) were corrected prior to final analysis runs. No use errors remain unresolved."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum FEA with bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity and frictional contact is an established modeling approach for metallic implant constructs under quasi-static loading; supported by peer-reviewed literature.",
      "rationale": "The model form — implicit nonlinear FEA with bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity for Ti-6Al-4V and augmented Lagrange frictional contact — is well established for pedicle screw construct simulation under ASTM F1717 conditions. Multiple peer-reviewed publications (including Nagaraja et al. 2012, Goel et al. 2006, and FDA-referenced benchmarks) support this model form for the intended QoIs. Simplifications (no bone analog material nonlinearity, rigid fixture assumption) are consistent with prior validated studies."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from certified material test reports; geometry from calibrated CMM measurements; friction coefficient from dedicated tribology testing.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties (E=114 GPa, sigma_y=880 MPa, tangent modulus=1.2 GPa) were sourced from lot-specific certified material test reports traceable to ASTM E8 tensile testing. Rod and screw geometry was verified by coordinate measuring machine (CMM) measurements on three representative specimens. Friction coefficient (mu=0.20) was determined from dedicated pin-on-disc tribology testing of the Ti-6Al-4V/Ti-6Al-4V interface under dry conditions."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs from production lots; dimensional inspection confirms geometry within drawing tolerances; two independent laboratories.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested: six at Laboratory 1 (FDA/CDRH) and five at Laboratory 2 (DePuy Synthes). All specimens were from production lots with full traceability. Dimensional inspection of three randomly selected specimens per lot confirmed geometry within ±0.05 mm of nominal drawing dimensions. Inter-laboratory variability in measured QoIs was within 3.1%, confirming reproducibility."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions should span at least two clinically relevant loading rates or fixture configurations to confirm model generalizability.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under a single ASTM F1717 test condition (quasi-static, 5 mm/min displacement rate, standard fixture geometry). Only one loading rate and one fixture configuration were evaluated. This limits the ability to confirm model generalizability across the clinical loading envelope. Achieved level 2 is below the required level 3 for this factor; this shortfall is documented and accepted given the well-established nature of the ASTM F1717 protocol as a regulatory standard test."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) are demonstrably equivalent to the physical test configuration within stated tolerances.",
      "rationale": "A parameter equivalency table was prepared mapping each FEA input to its experimental counterpart with traceability documentation. Geometry: CMM-verified within 0.05 mm. Material properties: lot-specific CTRs. Loading rate: displacement-controlled at 5 mm/min in both FEA and test. Fixture geometry: CAD model of ASTM F1717 fixture used directly. Friction coefficient: tribology-tested. No unresolved equivalency gaps were identified."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison using E/uval metric; all three QoIs satisfy E/uval < 1.96 and percent difference < 10%.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs were compared quantitatively: construct stiffness (E/uval=0.87, 4.2% difference), yield force (E/uval=1.41, 6.8% difference), and force at 40 mm displacement (E/uval=1.55, 7.3% difference). All three QoIs satisfy both acceptance bounds (E/uval < 1.96; percent difference < 10%). Validation uncertainty (uval) was computed from experimental repeatability across N=11 specimens and two laboratories using the method of ASME V&V 40 Section 5.3."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) are directly relevant to the regulatory submission claim and to clinical failure modes of pedicle screw constructs.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and referenced in FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions. These QoIs directly characterize the structural performance envelope relevant to fatigue life prediction and clinical failure (rod fracture, screw pullout). The QoIs are therefore directly relevant to both the regulatory claim and the clinical risk."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
